            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-06-17T16:15:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-06-17T16:15:00-05:00" n="195"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d195">
                <head>195. Memorandum of Telephone Conversation Between the Assistant Secretary of
                    State for Inter-American Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_HHF1"
                    >Holland</persName>) and Secretary of State <persName corresp="#p_DJF1"
                        >Dulles</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d195fn1">Source: <persName corresp="#p_EDD1"
                            >Eisenhower</persName> Library, <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">John Foster
                            Dulles</persName> Papers, <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">J.F.
                            Dulles</persName> Telephone Conversations, Box 2, A 67–28. No
                        classification marking. Transcribed by <persName>Phyllis
                        Bernau</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                        type="conversation-or-meeting-date" when="1954-06-17T17:15:00-04:00">June
                        17, 1954, 5:15 p.m.</date>
                </dateline>
                <p rend="center">TELEPHONE CALL FROM MR. <persName corresp="#p_HHF1"
                        >HOLLAND</persName>
                </p>
                <p>He said Sec. <persName>Anderson</persName> just told him that he has a military
                    telegram from Honduras that Armas(?) “is moving’. The Sec. said he didn’t know
                    what that means, but he supposes it means something. H. said A. is a
                    revolutionary individual lurking in the forest.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
